        "Body":  "Take -Time Tuesdays: Message from Kimberly Johnson

As we strive to manage our previous commitments and prioritize new, crisis-related initiatives, I recognize that we just don't have the capacity to do it all. Some of our efforts will need to slow down and others will need to be put on pause for another time. Our leadership team is working on a high-level prioritization list, and we will start socializing it next week.  

 

There is something else we want to start next week, too. As Gene Kim wrote in "The Phoenix Project," improvement of daily work is more important than daily work itself. The idea is that over the long run, finding ways to do your work more efficiently brings greater returns than just doing more of the same work. At a moment like this, when we just can't find enough time to do everything that needs to get done, it is essential that we invest in improving our daily work.  In order to facilitate this investment, that, the COO leadership team is committing to freeing up 10% of your workday so that you can look for continuous improvement opportunities and bring more efficiency to your daily work. 

 

Starting on Tuesday, April 7, our division will not schedule meetings after 1 p.m. on Tuesdays.  Please use this time to improve your daily work and make it easier on yourself and your teams. We will collect the best continuous improvement ideas and share them back with all of you. Please enjoy — 'Take Time Tuesdays'. ​​

        "Body":  " 

We’re writing to say “thank you” in a very tangible way for everything you’ve done over the past few months. Starting Friday, June 12, and continuing through the Labor Day weekend, our weekends will begin each Friday at 1 p.m. your local time. 

As leaders of the company, we deeply appreciate your dedication to our mission and flexibility as we’ve operated remotely due to the pandemic. We understand the professional and personal challenges you are navigating during this time of uncertainty and stress in our nation. We are incredibly proud of our One Fannie Mae team. Each of you is contributing to the company’s success and allowing us to deliver help to our customers, homeowners, and renters through this tough period.

We hope you can use these “group release” afternoons to unplug, take care of yourself, enjoy time with your loved ones, and soak up the summer weather. Giving this time back to you is one way for us to express our recognition for everything you’re doing.

Given the nature of their work, some employees may need to continue supporting customer and business needs on Friday afternoons and should consult with their managers on alternative flexible arrangements. Please check HomeSite for more information on how to log your summer hours <https://click.e.fanniemae.com/?qs=a09450b914dae3c3620e4729520e2901b057349359822e57517d3dbfb06947c3f1cf4fb4f8c74842af8d64728dadd8c96aa9a37ea3319b65>  in Payroll Connect. As Friday, July 3, is a company holiday, early release that week will be on Thursday, July 2.

Thank you again for your continued commitment. Enjoy your first summer hours this Friday — we know we will!

Hugh & Dave

        "Body":  "Let’s get together to review the work to start our new sprint. 

 

This is our Jira board

CollabEng Jira Board <https://jira:8443/secure/RapidBoard.jspa?rapidView=42617&projectKey=OTEITDWP13&view=planning.nodetail&selectedIssue=OTEITDWP13-69&issueLimit=100> 

 

Goals for the meeting:

1.	Prioritize Backlog
2.	Establish / Refine User Story (Backlog items) 

	a.	Verify they are:

                                                              i.      Independent (Can this User Story be done within the Scrum Team Squad? User Stories can have sub tasks assign to different people that belong to our Scrum Team Squad)  

                                                             ii.      Negotiable (A story is not a contract.  A story is an invitation to a conversation.  The story captures the essence of what is desired.)

                                                           iii.      Valuable (What is the value of the outcome?) 

                                                           iv.      Estimable (Assign story points)

                                                             v.      Small enough (Do we need to separate this User Story into smaller User Stories or can we accomplish desired outcome within the Sprint timebox?)

                                                           vi.      Testable (Can you show evidence of the desired outcome)  

	b.	Acceptance Criteria

                                                              i.      How do we know when the User story is Done? 

 

NOTE:  We will have training sessions in place to understand, sizing, grooming, how to use Jira, etc.  TEAM work.  

 

 

Retro:  Adding an additional 15 minutes to introduce a Retrospective 

"What did we do well?" and "What should have we done better?"

        "Body":  "Goals for the meeting:

1.	Build and prioritize backlog
2.	Prepare for our next sprint
3.	Establish / Refine User Story (Backlog items) 

	a.	Verify they are:

                                                              i.      Independent (Can this User Story be done within the Scrum Team Squad? User Stories can have sub tasks assign to different people that belong to our Scrum Team Squad)  

                                                             ii.      Negotiable (A story is not a contract.  A story is an invitation to a conversation.  The story captures the essence of what is desired.)

                                                           iii.      Valuable (What is the value of the outcome?) 

                                                           iv.      Estimable (Assign story points)

                                                             v.      Small enough (Do we need to separate this User Story into smaller User Stories or can we accomplish desired outcome within the Sprint timebox?)

                                                           vi.      Testable (Can you show evidence of the desired outcome)  

	b.	Acceptance Criteria

                                                              i.      How do we know when the User story is Done?

        "StartUTC":  "/Date(1606250700000)/",
        "Body":  "The purpose of these stand-ups is for the squad to quickly communicate individual progress towards our sprint goals. This time should not be used for detailed status updates or for solutioning issues, but seen as your opportunity to inform the rest of the squad about how your work is going, share important information and ask for help when needed. The tone should be light and fun, but informative.

 

DWP Conference Tools JIRA Board <https://jira:8443/secure/RapidBoard.jspa?rapidView=44446&projectKey=OTEITDWP24> 

 

Agenda:

 

Each team member should aim to answer the following questions in less than two minutes:

1)      What did you work on or complete yesterday?

2)      What will you work on or complete today?

3)      Do you have any blockers or impediments?

4)      Are there any critical updates that others should be made aware of?

 

Meeting Norms:

 

Attendance

*	Be on time, start on time, end on time
*	If you cannot attend a huddle, ask someone who attended what was discussed
*	If you are late to a huddle, ask someone offline what was discussed

Behavior

*	Participants understand that their feedback is critical to the discussion and learning of the team

	*	Effective challenge is welcomed regardless of domain expertise

*	Participants respectfully avoid multitasking and remain mentally present for the duration

Facilitation

*	Follow the rotation
*	For topics that require additional conversation, add it to the Parking Lot and assign an owner.

	*	Use ELMO – “Enough, let’s move on”

*	Facilitator wraps up huddle on time

Preparation

*	All updates are made before the huddle (preferably made by COB the day before)

        "Body":  "This squad’s PI Planning sessions are part of the overall DW PI Planning activities that are taking place on Mon, Jan 11th through Wed, Jan 13th. We’ll use our time together to complete the following activities over the course of these sessions:

 

1.	Review the DWP Conference Tools JIRA board <https://jira:8443/projects/OTEITDWP24/summary> 

	a.	Make any configuration changes that will allow the team to best utilize going forward

2.	Review existing epics on the DWP Epic Kanban board <https://jira:8443/secure/RapidBoard.jspa?projectKey=OTEITDWP&rapidView=8102> 

	a.	Make any necessary updates to all of the team’s epics

3.	Review existing features on the DWP Feature Kanban board <https://jira:8443/secure/RapidBoard.jspa?rapidView=42901&projectKey=OTEITDWP> 

	a.	Make any necessary updates to all of the team’s features

4.	Brainstorm new high-level activities that we want to complete in PI #3 (Feb 16th – Apr 26th)

	a.	Add these activities to the epic or feature boards as needed

5.	Review the stories and sub-tasks that are highlighted in gray in the attached spreadsheet

	a.	Move these from the Smart Workplace board <https://jira:8443/projects/OTSW/summary>  to our new board as needed

6.	Review current backlog and assign stories to our next sprint (Jan 19th – Feb 1st)
7.	Assign backlog tasks to PI #3 sprints (31-35)
8.	Review tasks assigned to sprints 31-35 and determine internal and external dependencies
9.	Create dependency tasks and assign to other teams (if applicable)
10.	Groom/refine epics, features, stories and sub-tasks by adding the following details:

	a.	Priority
	b.	Descriptions
	c.	Acceptance Criteria
	d.	Assignees
	e.	Story Points
	f.	Labels

 

While we complete this exercise, especially the brainstorming activity, please keep the following prioritization categories in mind:



 

Thank you all so much in advance for your dedication to the outcome of these sessions. Please feel free to reach out at any time with any questions, comments or concerns.

        "Body":  "Take -Time Tuesdays: Message from Kimberly Johnson

As we strive to manage our previous commitments and prioritize new, crisis-related initiatives, I recognize that we just don't have the capacity to do it all. Some of our efforts will need to slow down and others will need to be put on pause for another time. Our leadership team is working on a high-level prioritization list, and we will start socializing it next week.  

 

There is something else we want to start next week, too. As Gene Kim wrote in "The Phoenix Project," improvement of daily work is more important than daily work itself. The idea is that over the long run, finding ways to do your work more efficiently brings greater returns than just doing more of the same work. At a moment like this, when we just can't find enough time to do everything that needs to get done, it is essential that we invest in improving our daily work.  In order to facilitate this investment, that, the COO leadership team is committing to freeing up 10% of your workday so that you can look for continuous improvement opportunities and bring more efficiency to your daily work. 

 

Starting on Tuesday, April 7, our division will not schedule meetings after 1 p.m. on Tuesdays.  Please use this time to improve your daily work and make it easier on yourself and your teams. We will collect the best continuous improvement ideas and share them back with all of you. Please enjoy — 'Take Time Tuesdays'. ​​

Thank you again for your continued commitment. Enjoy your first summer hours this Friday — we know we will!

Hugh & Dave

        "Body":  "Let’s get together to review the work to start our new sprint. 

 

This is our Jira board

CollabEng Jira Board <https://jira:8443/secure/RapidBoard.jspa?rapidView=42617&projectKey=OTEITDWP13&view=planning.nodetail&selectedIssue=OTEITDWP13-69&issueLimit=100> 

 

Goals for the meeting:

1.	Prioritize Backlog
2.	Establish / Refine User Story (Backlog items) 

	a.	Verify they are:

                                                              i.      Independent (Can this User Story be done within the Scrum Team Squad? User Stories can have sub tasks assign to different people that belong to our Scrum Team Squad)  

                                                             ii.      Negotiable (A story is not a contract.  A story is an invitation to a conversation.  The story captures the essence of what is desired.)

                                                           iii.      Valuable (What is the value of the outcome?) 

                                                           iv.      Estimable (Assign story points)

                                                             v.      Small enough (Do we need to separate this User Story into smaller User Stories or can we accomplish desired outcome within the Sprint timebox?)

                                                           vi.      Testable (Can you show evidence of the desired outcome)  

	b.	Acceptance Criteria

                                                              i.      How do we know when the User story is Done? 

 

NOTE:  We will have training sessions in place to understand, sizing, grooming, how to use Jira, etc.  TEAM work.

        "Body":  "Goals for the meeting:

                                                           iii.      Valuable (What is the value of the outcome?)

        "StartUTC":  "/Date(1606250700000)/",
        "Body":  "The purpose of these stand-ups is for the squad to quickly communicate individual progress towards our sprint goals. This time should not be used for detailed status updates or for solutioning issues, but seen as your opportunity to inform the rest of the squad about how your work is going, share important information and ask for help when needed. The tone should be light and fun, but informative.

 

DWP Conference Tools JIRA Board <https://jira:8443/secure/RapidBoard.jspa?rapidView=44446&projectKey=OTEITDWP24> 

 

Agenda:

 

Each team member should aim to answer the following questions in less than two minutes:

1)      What did you work on or complete yesterday?

2)      What will you work on or complete today?

3)      Do you have any blockers or impediments?

4)      Are there any critical updates that others should be made aware of?

 

Meeting Norms:

 

Attendance

*	Be on time, start on time, end on time
*	If you cannot attend a huddle, ask someone who attended what was discussed
*	If you are late to a huddle, ask someone offline what was discussed

Behavior

*	Participants understand that their feedback is critical to the discussion and learning of the team

	*	Effective challenge is welcomed regardless of domain expertise

*	Participants respectfully avoid multitasking and remain mentally present for the duration

Facilitation

*	Follow the rotation
*	For topics that require additional conversation, add it to the Parking Lot and assign an owner.

	*	Use ELMO – “Enough, let’s move on”

*	Facilitator wraps up huddle on time

Preparation

*	All updates are made before the huddle (preferably made by COB the day before)

        "Body":  "This squad’s PI Planning sessions are part of the overall DW PI Planning activities that are taking place on Mon, Jan 11th through Wed, Jan 13th. We’ll use our time together to complete the following activities over the course of these sessions:

 

1.	Review the DWP Conference Tools JIRA board <https://jira:8443/projects/OTEITDWP24/summary> 

	a.	Make any configuration changes that will allow the team to best utilize going forward

2.	Review existing epics on the DWP Epic Kanban board <https://jira:8443/secure/RapidBoard.jspa?projectKey=OTEITDWP&rapidView=8102> 

	a.	Make any necessary updates to all of the team’s epics

3.	Review existing features on the DWP Feature Kanban board <https://jira:8443/secure/RapidBoard.jspa?rapidView=42901&projectKey=OTEITDWP> 

	a.	Make any necessary updates to all of the team’s features

4.	Brainstorm new high-level activities that we want to complete in PI #3 (Feb 16th – Apr 26th)

	a.	Add these activities to the epic or feature boards as needed

5.	Review the stories and sub-tasks that are highlighted in gray in the attached spreadsheet

	a.	Move these from the Smart Workplace board <https://jira:8443/projects/OTSW/summary>  to our new board as needed

6.	Review current backlog and assign stories to our next sprint (Jan 19th – Feb 1st)
7.	Assign backlog tasks to PI #3 sprints (31-35)
8.	Review tasks assigned to sprints 31-35 and determine internal and external dependencies
9.	Create dependency tasks and assign to other teams (if applicable)
10.	Groom/refine epics, features, stories and sub-tasks by adding the following details:

	a.	Priority
	b.	Descriptions
	c.	Acceptance Criteria
	d.	Assignees
	e.	Story Points
	f.	Labels

 

While we complete this exercise, especially the brainstorming activity, please keep the following prioritization categories in mind:



 

Thank you all so much in advance for your dedication to the outcome of these sessions. Please feel free to reach out at any time with any questions, comments or concerns.
